    "recap_headline": "",
    "recap_text": "MANHATTAN, Kan. \u2013\nEight strikeouts from Cole Carlon and a solo homer by Landon Hairston helped Arizona State overcome a late one-run deficit to take a 5-4 series-opening victory Friday night at Tointon Family Stadium.\nTrailing 4-3 entering the eighth, ASU (16-5, 3-1 Big 12), which is ranked 24\nth\nby Baseball America, pushed a run across the plate on a double play to even the score before Hairston belted his ninth home run of the season for the go-ahead run.\n\"You'll have a couple of moments during a Friday night game in this conference where you have to capitalize, and we were unable to do that,\" said head coach\nPete Hughes\n. \"We did a very good job against [Cole Carlon], creating some offense. When you're at home, you want to have the lead late, were able to do that with big hits by Dee [Kennedy] and Carlos [Vasquez] but didn't play clean enough to sustain the lead and finish. Looking to play better in front of these great crowds and get back in this series tomorrow.\"\nK-State, (16-6, 2-2 Big 12) had seven different players produce a hit, including home runs by\nDee Kennedy\nand\nCadyn Karl\n. With his 10\nth\nhome run of the season, Kennedy became the fastest player to reach 10 homers in a single-season in the Hughes era.\nHOW IT HAPPENED\nAfter two scoreless frames, the Wildcats opened scoring as Karl launched his second homer of the season.\nASU responded with three runs over a two-inning span, highlighted by PJ Moutzouridis' solo blast to left.\nAdam Arther\nrelieved\nJames Guyette\nin the fifth and immediately picked up two quick outs to get out of the bases loaded jam and shift momentum to the Wildcats' dugout.\nDesignated hitter\nMicah Kendrick\nled off the bottom of the sixth with a single past the diving efforts of the Sun Devils' second baseman and was followed by Kennedy's 10\nth\nhomer of the year, marking his second straight season with double-digit homers.\nThe Wildcats took the lead in the seventh, as Vasquez singled down the right field line, scoring Kennedy from second.\nIn the top of the eighth, the Sun Devils erased the one-run deficit and took back the lead with a groundout to second and solo shot to right, making it 5-4.\nINSIDE THE BOX\nASU scored five runs on nine hits, with no errors and stranding 12 on base, while K-State scored four runs on seven hits, committed two errors and left 10 on base.\nSeven different Wildcats recorded a hit Friday.\nKennedy and Karl each homered.\nSix players hit for ASU, led by three from Brody Briggs while Dominic Smaldino added two.\nTazwell Buter (0-2) was tagged for the loss, surrendering the final two runs on two hits in his 1 1/3 relief outing.\nSean Fitzpatrick (2-0) was awarded the victory in relief, surrendering one run on one hit in 2/3 innings, while Derek Schaefer earned his third save.\nCarlon struck out eight over his five-inning start and allowed three runs (earned) on four hits with five walks.\nTEAM NOTES\nASU leads the all-time series 6-2, while Friday's contest marks the second ever meeting between the two squads in Manhattan. The series is now tied 1-1 in games played in Manhattan.\nIn 22 games, K-State has been held to five or fewer runs in seven.\nFriday's game marked the first loss when hitting two or more home runs, moving to 8-1.\nPLAYER NOTES\nIn eight games, Kennedy has stolen six bases. He leads the Big 12 with 14 stolen bases on the season.\nKennedy becomes the fastest player in the Hughes era to reach 10 home runs.\nKarl has homered in two straight games, totaling two in his collegiate career.\nON DECK\nGame two between the Wildcats and Sun Devils is scheduled for 4 p.m. CT at Tointon Family Stadium Saturday and can be seen on ESPN+ and the ESPN app.\n\u2013 k-statesports.com \u2013\nHow to follow the Cats:\nFor complete information on K-State Baseball, visit\nwww.kstatesports.com\nand follow the team's social media channels on\nX (formerly Twitter),\nInstagram\nand\nFacebook\n.",
